4.  `folio_test_dirty(folio)`: The folio is still dirty (needs to be written to swap).

Because of this, `isolate_folio` *skips* this dirty shmem folio!

Here’s the killer: When `isolate_folio` returns `false`, it's not isolated. So it is not added to the pages to be reclaimed (by `shrink_folio_list`). Since it's not isolated, the kernel *won't* write these pages back to swap. And because they're not written back, they remain dirty and in the swap cache! And it is skipped FOREVER!

Normally, `shrink_folio_list` is the function that actually writes out the swapped shmem folios. If a shmem folio is in the swap cache, `shrink_folio_list` correctly handles it, but *only* if `isolate_folio` returns true. Because `isolate_folio` returns false, it will be skipped by reclaim and MGLRU and it *will never* reach `shrink_folio_list` again!

This creates a livelock! The dirty shmem folios are effectively "stuck" in the swap cache, preventing them from being reclaimed and re-writing themselves. This means that under memory pressure (or if an attacker is able to induce swap congestion), you could get a permanent state where shmem pages will never be reclaimed, causing memory exhaustion and a potential denial-of-service, or DoS, by filling the page cache.

